text: The music at the end of the trailer does not fit at all.. A personal childhood favorite song from the first Jurassic Park accompanied by rough CGI, Godzilla-like noises from the new hybrid-Rex, and the stereotypical crowd running ruins it... I hate when they put contradictory music in trailers, ruins the anticipation and feel of the movie. Ruined my first impression of the film. Of course, as a Jurassic Park fan I will see it. Really not liking the train system, reminds me of something from The Hunger Games. I mean, it's cool and all they are making it more technological and advanced but it just seems to be so much more influenced on appealing the new generation than sticking to the true Jurassic Park core. I think it's really cool they're including aquatic creatures. I wish they didn't show that much in the trailer/spoilers and make a better first impression like the Interstellar trailers did. Ugh, I really hope it's going to turn out okay... Missing Alan Grant already, but he had his time in two Jurassic Park films already.

Forget Jaws, it has nothing on this thing. Secondly, the humans thought it was a good idea to make a dinosaur, which it seems like its some smarter, probably King Kong-sized T-Rex.  The¬†people¬†are screwed, this genetically engineered T-Rex is going to screw things up, allowing all the other dinosaurs to break out. They can't run from the dinosaurs, especially the velociraptors. In fact, the velociraptors alone will probably ruin all chances of escape. If an elephant were wandering near the seashore and one of these sea scorpions were alive today that is.  I found an article: ....On 20.11.2007 scientists who discovered the fossil claw of a giant sea scorpion in southern Germany say the find -- the biggest of its kind -- suggests similar ancient creatures were much larger than previously thought. German palaeontologist Markus Poschmann excavated the fossilized claw of the giant aquatic creature from 390 million-year-old rocks near the town of Pr√ºm in Rhineland Palatinate, the online journal Biology Letters reported on Tuesday, Nov. 20. The 46-centimeter (18-inch) claw probably came from an animal around 2.5 meters (eight feet, two inches) in length -- half a meter longer than any previously found. "This is an amazing discovery," said Simon Braddy from the Department of Earth Sciences at the University of Bristol in England, in a press release. Braddy, along with Poschmann from the General Department of Cultural Heritage in Rhineland-Palatinate and Erik Tetlie from Yale University, co-authored the report. Scientists surprised at size of find. ......There were also, colossal cockroaches, jumbo dragonflies, and Arthropleura, (giant centipede) that stretched up to 8.5 feet (2.6 meters) long and may have eaten both plants and small animals, ¬†which means, it could attack, and eat you too!

Even that one pushed it a little into Godzilla territory, but it was still rather good. I mean, resurrecting dinosaurs is one thing, but making a genetically modified, all new & approved killing machine for the fun of it after the events of the previous movies does seem a little implausible. The whole point of the park was to give the visitors an idea of what living, breathing dinosaurs from 65 million years ago looked & acted like in the flesh. Somewhere along the way, the late Michael Crichton's original idea got lost. Just an opinion, mind.
